BASICS:
    works on a system of tickets where principals (users and computers) are authenticated by a central, trusted server
    relies on shared-secret cryptography to establish trust with clients
    key distribution center (KDC):
        trusted source for authentication
        consists of a database of all principals and their associated password hashes, 
            an authentication server (AS), a ticket granting server (TGS)
        in a windows domain, the KDC would be the domain controller
    ticket granting ticket (TGT):
        provided to a principal after their identity has been verified 
        used in lieu of providing their password everytime they want to access a service
    service:
        a resource that can be accessed by a principal (e.g. SMB share, MSSQL, etc.)
        each service is identified by a SPN (i.e. class/instance:port)
    service ticket:
        to access a service using kerberos, the principal must request a service ticket from the TGS
        they send their TGT to the KDC and get a ticket granting service ticket in return
    privileged attribute certificate:
        structure that can be attached to a ticket which contains additional principal information
        the service will inspect the PAC to determine the user's privilege without querying from AD

    authentication overview:
        CLIENT      KDC      SERVICE
        AS-REQ ----> |
           | <---- AS-REP
        TGS-REQ----> |
           | <---- TGS-REP
        AP-REQ ---------------> |       NOTE: optional PAC validation here
           | <--------------- AP-REP

kerberos delegation is a feature that allows one principal to request access to resources on behalf of another principal
three types: unconstrained, constrained, role-based

    unconstrained delegation:
        enabled by setting a flag called TRUSTED_FOR_DELEGATION on the UAC attribute of the computer object
            we can check which copmuters have unconstrained using: 
                beacon> ldapsearch (&(samAccountType=805306369)(userAccountControl:1.2.840.113556.1.4.803:=524288)) --attributes samaccountname
        this can be abused since any copmuter configured for unconstrained delegation can be used to extract TGTs
        we can use rubeus' monitor command to capture and display TGTs as user authneticate
            beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\Rubeus\Rubeus\bin\Release\Rubeus.exe monitor /nowrap
    constrained delegation:
        Service for User (S4U) extension was created to replace unconstrained by limiting the services to which another service can delegate access
            Service for User to Proxy (S4U2proxy) allows a service to obtain a specified service ticket on behalf of a different user
                known as constrained delegation
            Service for User to Self (S4U2self) allows a service to obtain a service ticket on behalf of a user when a user authenticated in a way other than kerberos
                known as protocol transition 
        configured via the msDS-AllowedToDelegateTo attribute of the copmuter object
            we can check the list of SPNs that the computer is allowed to delegate to using:
                beacon> ldapsearch (&(samAccountType=805306369)(msDS-AllowedToDelegateTo=*)) --attributes samAccountName,msDS-AllowedToDelegateTo
        constrained delegation:
            used when only kerberos authentication is enabled 
            the service will send a TGS-REQ to the KDC asking for TGS to the target SPN and include a copy of the user's cached TGS
            the KDC will verify the msDS-AllowedToDelegateTo attribute contains the target SPN then return the service ticket
        protocol transition:
            disabled unless the TRUSTED_TO_AUTH_FOR_DELEGATION flag is explicitly set on the UAC attribute of the computer object
                we can check this using:
                    beacon> ldapsearch (&(samAccountType=805306369)(samaccountname=lon-ws-1$)) --attributes userAccountControl
                    NOTE: any value other than default 4096 should be inspected, decimal value for TRUSTED_TO_AUTH_FOR_DELEGATION is 16777216, so we would do [System.Convert]::ToBoolean(<UAC_value> -band 16777216) in PowerShell
            the service will send a TGS-REQ containing the user's username and sets the SPN to the copmuter's own samAccountName    